{"title":"Small Talk with Colleagues: Beyond the Weather","slug":"small-talk-colleagues-beyond-weather","description":"What can you say to colleagues after “How are you?” Learn safe workplace small talk topics, starters, and follow-up questions while you practice English vocabulary for real office conversations.","level":"B1","appUrl":"https://app.readerly.ai/story/ef5ab72c-cef3-4404-a2a7-e411789f83d3?utm_source=blog&utm_medium=word-banner&utm_campaign=small-talk-colleagues-beyond-weather","text":"Small talk at work is easier when you use safe, everyday topics. Weather is fine for one sentence, but good conversations usually move to weekend plans, shows, food, sports, or travel. The goal is not to be funny. The goal is to sound friendly and give your colleague an easy way to answer.\n\nOn Friday, try: “Do you have any plans for the weekend?” On Monday, ask: “How was your weekend?” Good follow-up questions are short: “Where did you go?” “Was it relaxing?” or “Would you do it again?” If the answer is short, smile and move on.\n\nShows and movies are useful because many people enjoy them. You can say: “Have you watched anything good lately?” or “I need a new show. Any recommendations?” Follow up with: “What kind of show is it?” or “What do you like about it?”\n\nFood is also easy. At lunch, ask: “Where did you get that?” or “Have you tried the café downstairs?” You can follow with: “What do you usually order?” Avoid strong negative comments about someone’s food.\n\nSports and travel are good only when the other person seems interested. Try: “Are you following any teams this season?” or “Are you going anywhere this summer?” Follow up with: “How is your team doing?” or “What did you like most about the trip?” Avoid personal questions about money.\n\nTo end politely, say: “Anyway, I should get back to work,” or “Good talking with you. See you in the meeting.” Small talk is a small skill, but it helps colleagues feel comfortable working together.","words":{"0":{"word":"sma